  "response": "A 20,000 3D score in AnTuTu benchmark is *very* low by today's standards.  Here's a breakdown of what that means in terms of expectations:\n\n*   **Very old devices:** This score likely indicates a device that's several years old (e.g., around 2012-2014).\n*   **Low-end/Budget devices:** Even some modern ultra-budget phones would score higher.\n\n**What to expect from a device with this 3D performance:**\n\n*   **Gaming:**\n    *   **Extremely limited.** You'll likely only be able to play *very* basic 2D games smoothly (think simple puzzle games, card games).\n    *   Most 3D games will be unplayable or run with extremely low frame rates (single digits), heavy lag, and low resolution settings. Forget about playing popular titles like PUBG Mobile, Fortnite, Genshin Impact, etc.\n*   **General Usage:**\n    *   **Lag and stutters.** Expect lag when navigating the user interface, opening apps, and multitasking.\n    *   **Video Playback:** Might struggle with higher-resolution videos (1080p or higher). 720p might be watchable, but don't expect smooth playback on demanding scenes.\n    *   **Web Browsing:** Can be slow, especially with websites that have a lot of images or scripts.\n*   **Graphics Quality:**\n    *   **Very low.** You'll see heavily simplified textures, low polygon counts, and minimal special effects in any 3D application.\n\n**In short: Expect a very limited experience with 3D applications and games.**\n\n**Context is Key:**\n\n*   **The AnTuTu version matters:** AnTuTu scores can vary significantly between different versions of the benchmark. Ensure you are comparing to similar scores using the same version.\n*   **Age of the device:**  A 20,000 3D score on a phone released in 2012 might have been respectable at the time, but completely inadequate today.\n\n**Overall Recommendation:**\n\nIf you are using a device that scores around 20,000 in AnTuTu 3D, you likely need an upgrade if you want to enjoy modern mobile gaming, demanding apps, or smooth performance in general.\n",
